male":"1333–Overleden","1295–1366":"1295–1366","1270–Female":"1270–Overleden","1337":"1337","circa 1330":"circa 1330","1366":"1366","1333":"1333","1453":"1453","1330":"1330","1295":"1295","1382":"1382","1270":"1270","England":"England"},"en":{"circa 1330–":"about 1330–Deceased","1330–Male":"1330–Deceased","1333–Female":"1333–Deceased","1295–1366":"1295–1366","1270–Female":"1270–Deceased","1337":"1337","circa 1330":"about 1330","1366":"1366","1333":"1333","1453":"1453","1330":"1330","1295":"1295","1382":"1382","1270":"1270","England":"England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"of","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["German: possibly a metonymic occupational name for a fisherman, from <i>orfe</i>, a species of freshwater fish. Alternatively, a habitational name from Urff near Kassel, formerly Orpha."],"variants":[{"name":"Orff","meanings":["German: variant of   Orf  ."]}]},{"name":"Milton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and Scottish: habitational name from one or other of the many places called Milton, or sometimes Middleton (see   Middleton  ) and occasionally Melton (see   Melton  ), most of which derive from Old English <i>middel</i> ‘middle’ or <i>myln</i> ‘mill’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’."],"variants":[{"name":"Middleton","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of the places so called. In over thirty instances from many different areas, the name is from Old English <i>midel</i> ‘middle’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘enclosure, settlement’. However, Middleton on the Hill near Leominster in Herefordshire appears in Domesday Book as <i>Miceltune</i>, the first element clearly being Old English <i>micel</i> ‘large’, ‘great’ (see   Middlebrook  ). Middleton Baggot and Middleton Priors in Shropshire have early spellings that suggest <i>gem̄thhyll</i> (from <i>gem̄th</i> ‘confluence’ + <i>hyll</i> ‘hill’) + <i>tūn</i> as the origin. This surname is also found in Scotland and Ireland.","History: A Scottish family of this name derives it from lands at Middleto(u)n near Kincardine. The Scottish physician Peter Middleton practiced in New York City after 1752 and was one of the founders of the medical school at King's College (now Columbia University) in 1767. One of the earliest of the Charleston, SC, Middleton family of prominent legislators was Arthur Middleton, born in Charleston in 1681. The name has also been established in Ireland since at least the 13th century; its presence was reinforced by settlers in the 17th century."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705193,"age":7,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705195,"age":52,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir William de Louches, of Milton was born about 1330, in England, his father, John de Louches of Milton, was 36 and his mother, Lady Ellen Wace, was 62. He had at least 1 daughter."},"et":{"circa 1330–":"umbes 1330–Surnud","1330–Male":"1330–Surnud","1333–Female":"1333–Surnud","1295–1366":"1295–1366","1270–Female":"1270–Surnud","1337":"1337","circa 1330":"umbes 1330","1366":"1366","1333":"1333","1453":"1453","1330":"1330","1295":"1295","1382":"1382","1270":"1270","England":"England"},"fi":{"circa 1330–":"noin 1330–Kuollut","1330–Male":"1330–Kuollut","1333–Female":"1333–Kuollut","1295–1366":"1295–1366","1270–Female":"1270–Kuollut","1337":"1337","circa 1330":"noin 1330","1366":"1366","1333":"1333","1453":"1453","1330":"1330","1295":"1295","1382":"1382","1270":"1270","England":"England"},"fr":{"circa 1330–":"environ 1330–Décédé","1330–Male":"1330–Décédé","1333–Female":"1333–Décédée","1295–1366":"1295–1366","1270–Female":"1270–Décédée","1337":"1337","circa 1330":"environ 1330","1366":"1366","1333":"1333","1453":"1453","1330":"1330","1295":"1295","1382":"1382","1270":"1270","England":"Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Lorsque Sir William de Louc